# Constraints

These rules apply to the Rust `squid` library in `crates/squid` (and its wasm/napi shims must stay thin).

## Never re-implement Poulpy internals

If a primitive exists in `poulpy-core`, `poulpy-schemes`, `poulpy-hal`, or `poulpy-cpu-ref`, use it. Writing a "simpler" version in squid defeats the purpose and will drift from Poulpy's correctness guarantees.

## Never add dependencies without checking Poulpy first

Poulpy already pulls in most primitives (RNGs, serialization, SIMD helpers). Adding duplicates fragments the dependency tree and risks version conflicts.

## Never expose scratch buffers in the public API

`ScratchOwned`, `Scratch`, and any `*_tmp_bytes` methods are internal. If you cannot hide scratch for a given operation, that is a design discussion, not a quiet API addition.

## Never expose prepared forms publicly

`FheUintPrepared`, `BDDKeyPrepared`, `GLWESecretPrepared` — these are implementation details inside `Context`, `SecretKey`, and `EvaluationKey` (only as private fields of those opaque types). Users must never construct or hold them outside squid’s wrappers.

## Never expose `Module<BE>` publicly

`Module<crate::backend::BE>` lives inside `Context`. It must not appear in any public type signature.

## Never add backend-generic code to the public API

`<BE: Backend>` generics must not appear in any public type or function. Backend dispatch is an internal concern.

## Never wrap poulpy-core directly (yet)

squid's entry point is `poulpy-schemes::bin_fhe::bdd_arithmetic`. Direct wrapping of raw GLWE, GGSW, or LWE primitives is out of scope until a concrete use case requires it.
